vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.openWithoutArgumentsInNewWindow.o: Focus the last active running instance.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.openWithoutArgumentsInNewWindow:
Controls whether a new empty window should open when starting a second instance without arguments or if the last running instance should get focus.
Note that there can still be cases where this setting is ignored (e.g. when using the `--new-window` or `--reuse-window` command line option).
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.reopenFolders.folders: Reopen all folders. Empty workspaces will not be restored.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.reopenFolders.none: Never reopen a window. Always start with an empty one.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.restoreWindows: Controls how windows are being reopened after a restart.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.restoreFullscreen: Controls whether a window should restore to full screen mode if it was exited in full screen mode.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.zoomLevel: Adjust the zoom level of the window. The original size is 0 and each increment above (e.g. 1) or below (e.g. -1) represents zooming 20% larger or smaller. You can also enter decimals to adjust the zoom level with a finer granularity.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.newWindowDimensions.default: Open new windows in the center of the screen.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.newWindowDimensions.inherit: Open new windows with same dimension as last active one.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.newWindowDimensions.offset: Open new windows with same dimension as last active one with an offset position.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.newWindowDimensions.fullscreen: Відкрити нові вікна на повний екран.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.newWindowDimensions: Controls the dimensions of opening a new window when at least one window is already opened. Note that this setting does not have an impact on the first window that is opened. The first window will always restore the size and location as you left it before closing.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.closeWhenEmpty: Controls whether closing the last editor should also close the window. This setting only applies for windows that do not show folders.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.autoDetectHighContrast: If enabled, will automatically change to high contrast theme if Windows is using a high contrast theme, and to dark theme when switching away from a Windows high contrast theme.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.doubleClickIconToClose: If enabled, double clicking the application icon in the title bar will close the window and the window cannot be dragged by the icon. This setting only has an effect when `#window.titleBarStyle#` is set to `custom`.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.titleBarStyle: Adjust the appearance of the window title bar. On Linux and Windows, this setting also affects the application and context menu appearances. Changes require a full restart to apply.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.nativeTabs: Enables macOS Sierra window tabs. Note that changes require a full restart to apply and that native tabs will disable a custom title bar style if configured.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.nativeFullScreen: Визначає чи нативний повноекранний режим повинен використовуватись у macOS. Вимкніть це налаштування, щоб macOS не створювала новий простір при переході в повноекранний режим.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.window.clickThroughInactive: If enabled, clicking on an inactive window will both activate the window and trigger the element under the mouse if it is clickable. If disabled, clicking anywhere on an inactive window will activate it only and a second click is required on the element.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.telemetry.enableCrashReporting:
Enable crash reports to be sent to a Microsoft online service. 
This option requires restart to take effect.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.argv.locale: The display Language to use. Picking a different language requires the associated language pack to be installed.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.argv.disableHardwareAcceleration: Disables hardware acceleration. ONLY change this option if you encounter graphic issues.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.argv.disableColorCorrectRendering: Resolves issues around color profile selection. ONLY change this option if you encounter graphic issues.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.argv.forceColorProfile: Allows to override the color profile to use. If you experience colors appear badly, try to set this to `srgb` and restart.
vs/workbench/electron-browser/desktop.co.argv.force-renderer-accessibility: Forces the renderer to be accessible. ONLY change this if you are using a screen reader on Linux. vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.editorTabCloseButton: Controls the position of the editor's tabs close buttons, or disables them when set to 'off'.

vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.editor.tabSizing.shrink: Allow tabs to get smaller when the available space is not enough to show all tabs at once.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.tabSizing: Controls the sizing of editor tabs.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.editor.splitSizingDistribute: Splits all the editor groups to equal parts.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.editor.splitSizingSplit: Splits the active editor group to equal parts.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.splitSizing: Controls the sizing of editor groups when splitting them.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.focusRecentEditorAfterClose: Controls whether tabs are closed in most recently used order or from left to right.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.showIcons: Controls whether opened editors should show with an icon or not. This requires an icon theme to be enabled as well.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.enablePreview: Controls whether opened editors show as preview. Preview editors are reused until they are pinned (e.g. via double click or editing) and show up with an italic font style.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.enablePreviewFromQuickOpen: Controls whether editors opened from Quick Open show as preview. Preview editors are reused until they are pinned (e.g. via double click or editing).
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.closeOnFileDelete: Controls whether editors showing a file that was opened during the session should close automatically when getting deleted or renamed by some other process. Disabling this will keep the editor open  on such an event. Note that deleting from within the application will always close the editor and that dirty files will never close to preserve your data.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.editorOpenPositioning: Controls where editors open. Select `left` or `right` to open editors to the left or right of the currently active one. Select `first` or `last` to open editors independently from the currently active one.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.sideBySideDirection: Controls the default direction of editors that are opened side by side (e.g. from the explorer). By default, editors will open on the right hand side of the currently active one. If changed to `down`, the editors will open below the currently active one.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.closeEmptyGroups: Controls the behavior of empty editor groups when the last tab in the group is closed. When enabled, empty groups will automatically close. When disabled, empty groups will remain part of the grid.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.revealIfOpen: Controls whether an editor is revealed in any of the visible groups if opened. If disabled, an editor will prefer to open in the currently active editor group. If enabled, an already opened editor will be revealed instead of opened again in the currently active editor group. Note that there are some cases where this setting is ignored, e.g. when forcing an editor to open in a specific group or to the side of the currently active group.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.mouseBackForwardToNavigate: Navigate between open files using mouse buttons four and five if provided.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.restoreViewState: Restores the last view state (e.g. scroll position) when re-opening files after they have been closed.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.centeredLayoutAutoResize: Controls if the centered layout should automatically resize to maximum width when more than one group is open. Once only one group is open it will resize back to the original centered width.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.limitEditorsEnablement: Controls if the number of opened editors should be limited or not. When enabled, less recently used editors that are not dirty will close to make space for newly opening editors.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.limitEditorsMaximum: Controls the maximum number of opened editors. Use the `#workbench.editor.limit.perEditorGroup#` setting to control this limit per editor group or across all groups.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.perEditorGroup: Controls if the limit of maximum opened editors should apply per editor group or across all editor groups.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.commandHistory: Controls the number of recently used commands to keep in history for the command palette. Set to 0 to disable command history.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.preserveInput: Controls whether the last typed input to the command palette should be restored when opening it the next time.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.closeOnFocusLost: Controls whether Quick Open should close automatically once it loses focus.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.quickOpen.preserveInput: Controls whether the last typed input to Quick Open should be restored when opening it the next time.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.openDefaultSettings: Controls whether opening settings also opens an editor showing all default settings.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.useSplitJSON: Controls whether to use the split JSON editor when editing settings as JSON.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.openDefaultKeybindings: Controls whether opening keybinding settings also opens an editor showing all default keybindings.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.sideBarLocation: Controls the location of the sidebar and activity bar. They can either show on the left or right of the workbench.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.panelDefaultLocation: Controls the default location of the panel (terminal, debug console, output, problems). It can either show at the bottom, right, or left of the workbench.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.statusBarVisibility: Controls the visibility of the status bar at the bottom of the workbench.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.activityBarVisibility: Controls the visibility of the activity bar in the workbench.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.viewVisibility: Controls the visibility of view header actions. View header actions may either be always visible, or only visible when that view is focused or hovered over.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.fontAliasing: Controls font aliasing method in the workbench.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.fontAliasing.default: Sub-pixel font smoothing. On most non-retina displays this will give the sharpest text.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.fontAliasing.antialiased: Smooth the font on the level of the pixel, as opposed to the subpixel. Can make the font appear lighter overall.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.fontAliasing.none: Disables font smoothing. Text will show with jagged sharp edges.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.workbench.fontAliasing.auto: Applies `default` or `antialiased` automatically based on the DPI of displays.
vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.settings.editor.desc: Determines which settings editor to use by default.

vs/workbench/browser/workbench.contribut.separator: `${separator}`: a conditional separator (" - ") that only shows when surrounded by variables with values or static text.

vs/workbench/contrib/terminal/browser/te.terminal.integrated.enableBell: Controls whether the terminal bell is enabled.
